post: Real time bidding. New loss function.Online advertising , Real time bidding.In general there are two task in real time bidding.First is a task of optimizing requests choice, second is a optimizing bid prices.A first task answers on a question , what need to buy, to get a revenue.The revenue is get from the target events: Clicks, Conversions ‚Ä¶So we may make a model that predict the events. It‚Äôs a classification task and may be solve as usual classification problem of binary classification.A second task answers on a question , what price need, to get a more benefit and win an auction .I consider the second task.The second is more complex, need increase number of win bids. Because only a wining bid gives revenue.The trivial solution is to set a bid price little smaller then an expected benefit, for example smaller by 10 % . But this solution is not optimal when there is a limit of our budget, and limits our benefit with 10%.Not bad solution is predict a probability of win and if the probability smaller then a given value increase a bid price. It‚Äôs a classification task too.But there is another way. Lets try to find an optimal price of the bid that layers between the loss price and win price, said for the same requests. And then if the win probability for this bid price smaller then some value, we increase the bid price.At first glance, this is a regression problem. But there is one problem. We only know the cost of losing when we lose the auction, but we don't know the next win price. In another case, we know the winning price when we won the auction, but we do not know the price of the next loss.And in general the bid price is a function of an input request. That is a set of categorical and numerical values.Such as : exchange id, app id, city, hour, day of week, language , and so on.Our model need to predict an optimal price for each request.My approach is to use a custom loss function that solves the problem. (I called loss YuLoss.)The loss function is based with MSE loss with little changes, or may base with any other regression loss.The main idea is :If the prediction price less or equivale then the loss price we penalty our model.If the prediction price more then the loss price we don‚Äôt penalty our model with MSE loss.If the prediction price less or equavile then the win price we don‚Äôt penalty our model.If the prediction price more then the win price we penalty our model with MSE loss.MSE (target, prediction) , if prediction <= target and result == no win else 0YuLoss =MSE (target, prediction), if prediction > target and result == win else 0The Model was made with using Catboost lib:Inputs: a list of vectors of categorical features.Targets : a list of prices and results - win/ no win.Data set of 10 M rows.The solution has given the optimal prices that in sum less then initial prices on 70 %.By the way a win rate decrease only 5%.The experiment was made with A\ B test.

It seems that the peak of the hype about the current version of chatGPT is over. And before OpenAI rolls out the next release, which in addition to text, seems to be able to do pictures and video, I want to voice a thought about the expectations of large language models. Someone finds a lot of the most unexpected applications for them, and someone says "chatGPT is a useless dumbass, doesn't know basic things, can't solve logical problems". But if you take what chatGPT can do as the part of the human brain that is responsible for speech, then chatGPT is already doing just fine. You don't have to expect outstanding abilities in logic, factual knowledge, mathematics, spatial orientation, etc.  As I see it, in solving the problem of creating general artificial intelligence, some chatGPT analogue will act as a convenient speech interface between humans, and more specialized things - "skills", like a notional Matlab, a data warehouse or home robot. Its task is to maintain the dialogue, translating from human to internal language of the respective skill, and vice versa.

The wave of popularity of chatGPT has reached me. The impression is shocking in the best sense of the word.Getting access to it cost me 45 rubles (instructions for bypassing the sanctions ban on Russian numbers can be easily googled).What I have tried:1. Foreign language lessonsThe chat suggested different options for practicing English, talked to me sincerely about books, asking pertinent questions. I also taught a couple of words in Japanese. I asked him to ask five words in English so that I would answer him in Japanese (romaji, to be exact). At first, the chat forgot to remove the translation for the suggested words, but after a couple of instructions I understood the exercise (and even apologized).2. Help in creating a chapter for Naruto fanfiction.According to the plot, I had to describe the celebration of the birthday of the heiress of the Hyuga clan and reveal on it the internal conflicts of its two branches. The chat helped with the plan of the holiday, and with the nature of the possible claims between the ninja. At the same time, taking into account the cultural characteristics of Japan and the world of Naruto.3. Junior Data Scientist CVVideos on YouTube lie - chat knows how to write a resume.My observations:1. Chat holds the context of the dialogue. It is not clear if he can lose it at all.2. Typical chat response: warning that the answer belongs to the machine -> multiple answers -> conclusion.3. There is an emotional color in speech, but of a weakly expressed positive character. Chat often emphasizes its technological nature. According to personal feelings, the ideal interlocutor for all those topics that do not interest your friends. Finally someone to talk to about this!4. Responds quickly in English. In response to Russian speech, he often answers in English. With a direct request to translate something into Russian (I assume this also applies to other languages), the response speed is significantly reduced.P.S. For fans of Naruto anime. I tried to get the chat to figure out how many people can be in the main and side branches and how the branch system works in the perspective of past generations (conditionally, how the main branch has not degenerated if everyone except the eldest child of the main family is stigmatized). Here the chat broke and could not solve the problem. I had to invent it myself :) With a competent series of questions, I'm sure the chat can help many writers with their incomprehensible dilemmas.#chatGPT #datascience #anime #ml

Payment through scanning QR code is very common but do you know how many ways there are to do it? There are 4 ways, no matter whether you‚Äôre using PayPal, Stripe, Paytm, WeChat, or Alipay. Is this surprising to you? To understand this, we will answer to questions. The first question is who presents the QR code:1. You can present the QR code and the merchant scans the code for payment. This is called ‚Äòconsumer-presented mode, and what the merchant does is direct debit your account.2. Obviously, the other way is that the merchant presents the QR code for you to scan to pay the due amount. This is called ‚Äòmerchant-presented mode‚Äô and you grant the direct credit from your account.The second question is whether the QR code is dynamic or static:1. A dynamic QR code means the QR code will be generated when you present it, or it will automatically regenerate every few seconds. Because it is dynamically generated, it may contain rich information, such as the amount due, transaction type, etc.2. A static QR code is generated once and used everywhere. Usually, it only contains the account information. So there are 2*2=4 ways to scan a QR code, which are:1. Consumer-presented mode + static QR code2. Consumer-presented mode + dynamic QR code3. Merchant-presented mode + static QR code4. Merchant-presented mode + dynamic QR codeI‚Äôve created an image to illustrate these 4 cases and their classic scenarios. üëâ Over to you: I‚Äôve marked one of the scan-to-pay scenarios with a red alert symbol to indicate that a risk is present. As a result, they ensure efficiency, reliability, and ease of integration with other systems by providing a standard approach to designing and building APIs. Here are the most used styles:  üîπSOAP: Mature, comprehensive, XML-based Best for enterprise applications  üîπRESTful: Popular, easy-to-implement, HTTP methods Ideal for web services  üîπGraphQL: Query language, request specific data Reduces network overhead, faster responses  üîπgRPC: Modern, high-performance, Protocol Buffers Suitable for microservices architectures  üîπWebSocket: Real-time, bidirectional, persistent connections Perfect for low-latency data exchange  üîπWebhook: Event-driven, HTTP callbacks, asynchronous Notifies systems when events occur  Over to you: Are there any other famous styles we missed?  ‚Äî Get a Free System Design PDF (158 pages) by subscribing to our weekly newsletter today: https://bit.ly/3FEGliw #systemdesign #coding #interviewtips .

Hello everybody and let me explain how did I improve my SSI from 32 to 61 in two weeks.1. My profile. I filled all the information that I could (it is important to have two profiles English and Russian, but both of it you have to fill in ENGLISH): - headline: short description of the position I'm looking for;- contact info: phone number, email, birthday and link to your LinkedIn profile - MUST;- filled all possible (5-five) position that I can apply - for those who are currently open to work;- filled the "About" form, wrote briefly and constructively, put all great outcomes such as cost savings, improving processes, speeding up Time to market, etc.;- explained all my expirience regarding IT: Company, position, breif description of the company, responsibility&key achievemnts;- filled an "Education" form (if you were graduated as a specialist, put in a form grade "Master's degree);- I mentioned skills that I possess and use with high efficiency - you must fill at least 20 skills;- asked for recommendations and gave a couple of it from myself;- filled a section with my language skills.2. Connections. Every day I add peers from the network of my current connections and using Additional searching engine of LinkedIn. Use the form "Search" on the top of your LinkedIn page, the fill the position (for example, Project manager) and after it choose the country and locations. You have to add people only WITH short cover message, not without any kind of words!3. Liked posts and commented it. I always update my home page and have a look on the posts of my Network. It is ipmortant to pay attention to like and write comments below these posts because it affects your SSI score. Use hashtags (especially #linkedin) in each message.4. Created my own posts. It is simple and last, but not the least. Whether I have any sort of a curious article or I want to share my current SSI, I make a post on my page and show/share it with my network. It is establishing of my brand here. I do all these things daily and it became as a routine. Will see how will it help me (or not).¬†The next step is to pump "Build relationships" block to 25 from 25.Feel free to ask any questions! #linkedin #profilebuilding #selfsufficiency #networking #connections #connectingpeople #brand #education #educationalleadership #ssi
